(10, 1, '2023-06-10 04:02:38', '2023-06-10 04:02:38', 'Authorized in 1890, she launched on JuneÂ 10, 1893.Â <em>Massachusetts</em>Â served in theÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish%E2%80%93American_War\">Spanishâ€“American War</a>Â and took part in the blockades ofÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cienfuegos\">Cienfuegos</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_de_Cuba\">Santiago de Cuba</a>. After the war, she served with theÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Atlantic_Squadron\">North Atlantic Squadron</a>Â where she suffered an explosion in aÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gun_turret\">gun turret</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ship_grounding\">ran aground</a>Â twice. She was recommissioned in 1910 for annual cruises forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midshipman\">midshipmen</a>, and in 1917 she served as a training ship for gun crews forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I\">World WarÂ I</a>. Her final decommission was in MarchÂ 1919 under the nameÂ <em>Coast Battleship NumberÂ 2</em>Â so her name could be reused forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Dakota-class_battleship_(1920)\">USSÂ <em>Massachusetts</em>Â (BB-54)</a>. In 1921, she wasÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scuttling\">scuttled</a>Â in shallow water nearÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pensacola,_Florida\">Pensacola, Florida</a>, and used as a target for experimentalÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artillery\">artillery</a>. The wreck was declared the property of the State of Florida in 1956.', 'Hello S.Y.Bca', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-s-y-bca', '', '', '2023-06-12 04:21:10', '2023-06-12 04:21:10', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=10', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(11, 1, '2023-06-10 04:02:38', '2023-06-10 04:02:38', 'Authorized in 1890, she launched on JuneÂ 10, 1893.Â <em>Massachusetts</em>Â served in theÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish%E2%80%93American_War\">Spanishâ€“American War</a>Â and took part in the blockades ofÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cienfuegos\">Cienfuegos</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_de_Cuba\">Santiago de Cuba</a>. After the war, she served with theÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Atlantic_Squadron\">North Atlantic Squadron</a>Â where she suffered an explosion in aÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gun_turret\">gun turret</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ship_grounding\">ran aground</a>Â twice. She was recommissioned in 1910 for annual cruises forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midshipman\">midshipmen</a>, and in 1917 she served as a training ship for gun crews forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I\">World WarÂ I</a>. Her final decommission was in MarchÂ 1919 under the nameÂ <em>Coast Battleship NumberÂ 2</em>Â so her name could be reused forÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Dakota-class_battleship_(1920)\">USSÂ <em>Massachusetts</em>Â (BB-54)</a>. In 1921, she wasÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scuttling\">scuttled</a>Â in shallow water nearÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pensacola,_Florida\">Pensacola, Florida</a>, and used as a target for experimentalÂ <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artillery\">artillery</a>. The wreck was declared the property of the State of Florida in 1956.', 'Hello S.Y.Bca', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '10-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-10 04:02:38', '2023-06-10 04:02:38', '', 10, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=11', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(12, 1, '2023-06-10 04:09:48', '2023-06-10 04:09:48', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start writing!</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Hello world!', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-10 04:09:48', '2023-06-10 04:09:48', '', 1, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=12', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(13, 1, '2023-06-12 03:52:55', '2023-06-12 03:52:55', '<table role=\"presentation\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><b><a title=\"Ernest Rutherford\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest_Rutherford\">Ernest Rutherford</a></b>Â (1871â€“1937) was a New Zealand physicist who was a pioneering researcher in bothÂ <a title=\"Atomic physics\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_physics\">atomic</a>Â andÂ <a title=\"Nuclear physics\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_physics\">nuclear physics</a>. In early work, Rutherford discovered the concept of radioactiveÂ <a title=\"Half-life\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-life\">half-life</a>, the radioactive elementÂ <a title=\"Radon\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radon\">radon</a>, and differentiated and namedÂ <a title=\"Alpha decay\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_decay\">alpha</a>Â andÂ <a title=\"Beta particle\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_particle\">beta radiation</a>. This work formed the basis for aÂ <a title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry</a>, awarded in 1908. WithÂ <a title=\"Thomas Royds\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Royds\">Thomas Royds</a>, Rutherford developed the theory that alpha radiation isÂ <a title=\"Helium\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>Â nuclei, and also theorized that atoms have their charge concentrated in a very smallÂ <a title=\"Atomic nucleus\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_nucleus\">nucleus</a>, and thereby pioneered theÂ <a title=\"Rutherford model\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherford_model\">Rutherford model</a>Â of theÂ <a title=\"Atom\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom\">atom</a>. He went on to perform the first artificially inducedÂ <a title=\"Nuclear reaction\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_reaction\">nuclear reaction</a>Â in 1917 in experiments where nitrogen nuclei were bombarded with alpha particles. As a result, he discovered the emission of a subatomic particle which became known as theÂ <a title=\"Proton\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proton\">proton</a>. Rutherford spent his later years as director of theÂ <a title=\"Cavendish Laboratory\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavendish_Laboratory\">Cavendish Laboratory</a>Â in Cambridge. The chemical elementÂ <a title=\"Rutherfordium\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherfordium\">rutherfordium</a>Â was named after him in 1997. This photograph of Rutherford, published by theÂ <a title=\"George Grantham Bain\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Grantham_Bain\">Bain News Service</a>, was most likely taken in the 1920s.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Hello bca 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-bca-2', '', '', '2023-06-12 04:22:53', '2023-06-12 04:22:53', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=13', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(14, 1, '2023-06-12 03:52:50', '2023-06-12 03:52:50', '<table role=\"presentation\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><b><a title=\"Ernest Rutherford\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest_Rutherford\">Ernest Rutherford</a></b>Â (1871â€“1937) was a New Zealand physicist who was a pioneering researcher in bothÂ <a title=\"Atomic physics\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_physics\">atomic</a>Â andÂ <a title=\"Nuclear physics\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_physics\">nuclear physics</a>. In early work, Rutherford discovered the concept of radioactiveÂ <a title=\"Half-life\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-life\">half-life</a>, the radioactive elementÂ <a title=\"Radon\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radon\">radon</a>, and differentiated and namedÂ <a title=\"Alpha decay\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_decay\">alpha</a>Â andÂ <a title=\"Beta particle\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_particle\">beta radiation</a>. This work formed the basis for aÂ <a title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry</a>, awarded in 1908. WithÂ <a title=\"Thomas Royds\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Royds\">Thomas Royds</a>, Rutherford developed the theory that alpha radiation isÂ <a title=\"Helium\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>Â nuclei, and also theorized that atoms have their charge concentrated in a very smallÂ <a title=\"Atomic nucleus\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_nucleus\">nucleus</a>, and thereby pioneered theÂ <a title=\"Rutherford model\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherford_model\">Rutherford model</a>Â of theÂ <a title=\"Atom\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom\">atom</a>. He went on to perform the first artificially inducedÂ <a title=\"Nuclear reaction\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_reaction\">nuclear reaction</a>Â in 1917 in experiments where nitrogen nuclei were bombarded with alpha particles. As a result, he discovered the emission of a subatomic particle which became known as theÂ <a title=\"Proton\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proton\">proton</a>. Rutherford spent his later years as director of theÂ <a title=\"Cavendish Laboratory\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavendish_Laboratory\">Cavendish Laboratory</a>Â in Cambridge. The chemical elementÂ <a title=\"Rutherfordium\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherfordium\">rutherfordium</a>Â was named after him in 1997. This photograph of Rutherford, published by theÂ <a title=\"George Grantham Bain\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Grantham_Bain\">Bain News Service</a>, was most likely taken in the 1920s.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Hello bca 2', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '13-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-06-12 03:52:50', '2023-06-12 03:52:50', '', 13, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=14', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(15, 1, '2023-06-12 03:53:54', '2023-06-12 03:53:54', '<b><a title=\"\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_birds_of_Wallis_and_Futuna\">Sixty-two species of birds have been recorded in Wallis and Futuna</a></b>, a FrenchÂ <a title=\"Overseas collectivity\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overseas_collectivity\">overseas collectivity</a>Â inÂ <a title=\"Polynesia\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynesia\">Polynesia</a>Â in the Pacific Ocean. It consists of three main islands,Â <a title=\"Wallis (island)\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wallis_(island)\">Wallis</a>Â (Uvea),Â <a title=\"Futuna (Wallis and Futuna)\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futuna_(Wallis_and_Futuna)\">Futuna</a>, andÂ <a title=\"Alofi Island\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alofi_Island\">Alofi Island</a>, along with several islets. Of the sixty-two bird species of the territory, five wereÂ <a title=\"Introduced species\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introduced_species\">introduced</a>Â by humans. No species areÂ <a title=\"Endemism\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism\">endemic</a>Â to the islands, but there are endemicÂ <a title=\"Subspecies\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subspecies\">subspecies</a>Â of theÂ <a title=\"Collared kingfisher\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collared_kingfisher\">collared kingfisher</a>, theÂ <a title=\"Polynesian triller\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynesian_triller\">Polynesian triller</a>Â <i>(example pictured)</i>, theÂ <a title=\"Fiji shrikebill\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiji_shrikebill\">Fiji shrikebill</a>, and theÂ <a title=\"Polynesian starling\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynesian_starling\">Polynesian starling</a>. TheÂ <a title=\"Tongan ground dove\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tongan_ground_dove\">shy ground dove</a>Â has beenÂ <a title=\"Local extinction\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_extinction\">extirpated</a>Â from the islands, while theÂ <a title=\"Blue-crowned lorikeet\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue-crowned_lorikeet\">blue-crowned lorikeet</a>Â is locally extinct on Uvea.Â <i>Ducula david</i>, an extinct species ofÂ <a title=\"Imperial pigeon\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_pigeon\">imperial pigeon</a>, wasÂ <a title=\"Species description\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species_description\">described</a>Â fromÂ <a title=\"Fossil\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fossil#Subfossil\">subfossil</a>Â remains on the islands and is thought to have been widespread before the arrival of humans. (<b><a title=\"List of birds of Wallis and Futuna\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_birds_of_Wallis_and_Futuna\">FullÂ list...</a></b>)', 'Hello bca 3', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-bca-3', '', '', '2023-06-12 03:53:54', '2023-06-12 03:53:54', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=15', 0, 'post', '', 0),
